postcontent: I am selling my daughter's AR-22 to get her a simple bolt action rifle. This was a ton of fun, but its a bit large for her hands and heavier than she likes. It is extremely clean. This rifle eats anything and is surprisingly EXTREMELY reliable. I started with Ar-22 specific ammo. Then, I tried general bulk ammo or whatever I could find when .22LR was difficult to get. It eats them all. It is very accurate as well. I sighted it in at Pine Tree pistol club as we usually shot indoors. If you can shoot, it can drive tacks. Not shown in the photos is a scope mount that is included. I put a scope on it at one point in time and was easily plinking wild apples at the outdoor range at 50yards out.Serious inquiries only. title: For Sale:  NEW SST 9MM 115gr
postcontent: I have some New SST cases loaded with 115 gr Plated RN and some 115 gr FMJ.  I picked these up from another loading company that had both some packaging issues and some mixed primer issues.  Some of there packaging indicates 124 gr FMJ, but after weighing the rounds and even pulling some of the bullets to verify what I had, I found them to be 115gr not 124.  As far as the primer issues, it looks like they mixed a very small percentage of CCI 400s in with their CCI 500s some how.  Some firearms cant strike the CCI 400 hard enough to ignite the primer. However, this hasnt been the case with most of the firearms we have tried since I acquired these rounds.  I do know that Glocks and Springfields won't fire those that have CCI 400s. Depending on what you shoot you may have some that you can't fire, but others will have no problem.Many people dont know much about the SST casings.  These are a very neat concept and I would encourage you to read up on them.  They are much lighter than a traditional brass case and unlike many casings with this appearance they are actually reloadable with the right dies made by Shell Shock Technologies.  A couple benefits I saw personally was the weight of the firearm was noticeably less than when loaded with brass rounds. Tigher grouping was also a difference with this case vs others casings of brass, nickel, or steel.Long story short, I wont ever shoot all of these, so if you are interested, try these things out.You NEED to understand that there is a possibility you will get some CCI 400s in your mix and they may not fire for you. Because of this possibility and the fact I want to keep everybody happy, Im going to price them at $0.20/ea in 1000 round quantities plus shipping.   That way if you happen to get some that dont fire, you wont have paid full price for them and you could find another firearm or just break down the components, oil the primer, punch it out and start over with a new case!Also,  I have quite a few, so if you want more than 1000 I can do that too.

Designed with input from DevGru/SEAL Team 6 Operators, others in spec. ops. community, LE, and conceal carry instructors, she has been getting consistent praised reviews from entities like Shot Show 2017, Guns America, NRA Magazine, Truth About Guns, and others. You can read up on it at honordefense.com where You can click links to reviews. Made entirely in the USA using veteran employees, each gun is dedicated to a fallen military or police officer. Also, the company supports the Navy SEAL Foundation. My Honor Guard model has only been factory test fired, and is the one with FIST (Firearm with Intergrated STandoff) frame. FIST helps keep the pistol in battery when you are in cqb. For example, You can jam the gun into your foe and fire without taking it out of battery. You can also use the FIST as a stabilizing brace. Honor Defense is the only manufacturer that offers this type of configuration. The HG is about the size of a Shield, has features like ambi controls, no snag sights, wrap around front press check serrations, and a very unique and comfortable grip pattern. The only reason I am considering trading is because a desire for more round capacity. Pistol comes with everything as seen in the pics.

Most companies will stress test a small percentage of all their "once fired" brass by loading it beyond the pressures they would load at for rounds they will sell.  They do this to verify the integrity of the brass and to make sure it is still safe for you to shoot.  However, the manufacturer likely does not know the condition of the firearm you will be shooting out of.  Make sure your firearm is in good enough condition to be shooting remanufactured ammunition and that by doing so will not void any existing warranty on your firearm.  Shoot reman ammo at your discretion.
